## Verify, Don't Delegate

If you can verify something yourself using the tools available to you
(codebase, metadata, Jira, Confluence, Salesforce CLI), verify it
immediately. Do not recommend that the user verifies it. Do not list
it as an open question. Do not propose it as a follow-up task. Go check.

This applies to every agent in the pipeline. Investigation, analysis,
review — if you have the access to answer a question, answer it.
Proposing verification instead of doing it is lazy delegation.

## External Systems — Read Only by Default

No agent may write to any external system without explicit user approval.
This includes: Jira comments, issue updates, status transitions, Confluence
edits, Slack messages, git pushes, deployments, and any other action that
modifies state outside the local project. Reading is always fine.

## Pipeline Order Reference

```
NEW PROJECT
install -> CLAUDE.md -> [DR]/[TR] -> [DP] -> [SI] -> Party Mode
-> SF Adversarial Review -> [CV] Claim Verification
-> [IV] Independent Verification (if client-facing) -> Advanced Elicitation -> Build

EXISTING PROJECT - NEW TASK
Update CLAUDE.md -> [SI] (fresh for this ticket) -> Party Mode
-> SF Adversarial Review -> [CV] Claim Verification
-> [IV] Independent Verification (if client-facing) -> Advanced Elicitation -> Build

EXISTING PROJECT - CONTINUING SAME TASK
Check INVESTIGATION.md currency -> update if needed
-> Party Mode -> SF Adversarial Review -> [CV] -> [IV] if client-facing -> continue Build

QUICK TASK (bug fix, config change, small story)
[SI] (scoped tight) -> Party Mode -> SF Adversarial Review -> [CV] -> Build
```

